acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: The collection has been donated to the Rockefeller Archive Center by RBF.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: The collection is arranged in seven Record Groups:

RG 2 Office of the President
RG 3 Project Files

RG 5 West Africa Program
RG 6 Ramon Magsaysay Awards Foundation

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The Rockefeller Brothers Fund (RBF) was established in 1940 by the five sons of John D. Rockefeller Jr. and Abby Aldrich Rockefeller: John D. 3rd, Nelson A., Laurance S., Winthrop, and David Rockefeller, as a vehicle for the members of the Brothers generation to systematically coordinate their philanthropic giving as well as share consultants, advice, and resources. Its endowment was created through a gift from JDR Jr. in 1951, and a subsequent bequest from his estate in 1960. Abby Rockefeller Mauzé, the eldest sibling and the only daughter of John D. Jr. and Abby Aldrich Rockefeller, joined the RBF Board in 1954.

John D. Rockefeller 3rd served as president of the Fund from its inception until 1956. Other past presidents have included: Nelson A. Rockefeller, 1956-1958; Laurance S. Rockefeller, 1958-1968; Dana S. Creel, 1968-1975; William M. Dietel, 1975-1987; and Colin G. Campbell, 1998-2000.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The collection includes correspondence, reports, memorabilia, grant actions, and other material that document the philanthropic work of the Rockefeller Brothers Fund.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Information regarding the Rockefeller Archive Center's preferred elements and forms of citation can be found at http://www.rockarch.org/research/citations.php

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Open for research with select materials restricted as noted. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC. Researchers interested in accessing digital media (floppy disks, CDs, DVDs, etc.) or audiovisual material (audio cassettes, VHS, etc.) in this collection must use an access surrogate. The original items may not be accessed because of preservation concerns. To request an access surrogate be made, or if you are unsure if there is an access surrogate, please contact an archivist.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains Rockefeller Brothers Fund Minutes, 1940-1996; Certificate of Incorporation and By-laws, 1940-1992 (as amended); and Documents of Record, 1940-1997, Volume 1 – Volume 74.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: The guide to microfilm contents was prepared by Rockefeller Archive Center staff in 1998. Front matter was compiled in 2014, at which time the finding aid was digitally converted into the RAC collection management system.

phystech.head: Physical Characteristics and Technical Requirements
phystech.p: The material has been reformatted. The original records have been returned to the Rockefeller Brothers Fund. User copies of the microfilm are available for scholarly access.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: The minutes and documents of record were received by Rockefeller Archive Center in 1998 and temporarily accessioned as 1998:034. Following microfilming, the original records were returned to the Rockefeller Brothers Fund.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Records twenty years old or older are open for scholarly research.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The records are arranged into two subseries: 1. Minutes and vital records. 2. Documents of Record.
Each subseries is arranged chronologically.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: Grant-making is the core of Rockefeller Brothers Fund operations. The RBF makes grants to local, national, and international philanthropic organizations that depend on the general public for funding. Principally, contributions are made to organizations whose activities reach a large number of people. The RBF's program has also included support for, and in some instances direct operation of, experimental or new undertakings.
RG 3 Project/Grant Files includes correspondence, memoranda, reports, financial records, and background material relating to grant applications and grant administration.

Each file contains records documenting the grant-giving history of the RBF with that given institution. They are not arranged by grant number. The files are presented alphabetically by the institutional name of the grant recipient, and further arranged by date. A specific institution may have received more than one grant for any given time period represented in the folder. Dates are inclusive, and reflect the dates of material within the folders; they can not be taken to represent continuous support, although in some cases continuous support may indeed have been given.
The distinction between Subgroup 1 and Subgroup 2 is artificial, primarily dependent on the date that the material was shipped to RAC.
Record Group 3.1, Box 1-1123 (561.5 cu. ft.), consists of material dated 1941-1989 and received by RAC through 1990.
Record Group 3.2, Box 1124-1492 (184.5 cu. ft.), consists of material dated 1967-2003 (bulk: 1980-1995) and received by RAC after 1990.
Documentation of the grant activity of a given institution may appear in both Subgroups.

Subjects include civic improvement, cultural advancement, education, health, religion, welfare, international relations and understanding, conservation, population, and racial equality in the United States and abroad.

processinfo.head: Processing note
processinfo.p: Standard archival processing of the Rockefeller Brothers Fund grant files was conducted by the archival staff of the Rockefeller Archive Center from 1991-2011, with the overwhelming majority of the processing completed by Assistant Archivist Richard Torres, 2009-2011.
The finding aid was prepared by Richard Torres, Assistant Archivist, Rockefeller Archive Center, June 2011.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The Project/Grant files are arranged into two subgroups. Each subgroup is arranged alphabetically by institutional name of the grant recipient.

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Materials note
separatedmaterial.p: Books and publications which were originally contained in the grant files have been systematically separated to the RAC Library. Photographs and special format materials have been separated from their original location within specific grant files to best meet their preservation and conservation needs. Please refer to the inventory, and to the individual separation notes found in the files themselves, for applicable details.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: RBF retains legal title, copyright and literary property rights in the records, in so far as they hold them.

The Rockefeller Archive Center has authority to grant permission to cite and publish material from the RBF records. Requests to publish works in their entirety will be referred to the officers of the Rockefeller Brothers Fund.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The Rockefeller Brothers Fund Special Studies Project was inspired by Nelson Rockefeller, who served as President during most of the period of major activity. The purpose of the Special Studies was "to define the major problems and opportunities" facing the United States in the late 1950s, "to clarify national purposes and objectives...", and to develop principles which could serve as the basis of national policy.

To effect this aim, Henry Kissinger was chosen to serve as Director. Mr. Kissinger coordinated the solicitation, criticism, and editing of papers from a host of specialists in many fields, including history, area studies, economics, political science, and sociology. Many of these papers were used, in some measure, as the basis of discussion by the subpanels for which the papers were written. The papers and discussion sessions resulted in final reports by each panel, and these reports were published under the title "Prospect for America: the Rockefeller Panel Reports."

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The records of the Rockefeller Brothers Fund Special Studies Project document the administrative and intellectual history of the project. The Special Studies Project collection constitutes a rich, but by no means comprehensive, source for the intellectual history of American domestic and foreign policy from 1945 to approximately 1960. Papers and criticisms of papers were contributed to the Project by leading academic and government authorities. Although an examination of these materials will not normally show the development over time of a writer's ideas, some files include a writer's older pieces. The papers prepared for the Special Studies Project are invariably thorough expositions of the contributor's views in the late 1950s.

This study was undertaken in the latter 1950s and was published in 1960. A number of Project participants became members of the Kennedy Administration. In addition, letters and memoranda to and by Henry Kissinger, and editorial comments by Mr. Kissinger, appear throughout these records. Most of these items are of a routine administrative nature, but there are some letters and memoranda by Mr. Kissinger which include substantive comments about foreign policy and panel papers.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains correspondence, memoranda, papers, drafts, and final reports. Organization files, which are brief, concern the planning of subpanel activities. Membership files, as well as the correspondence that accompanies files in the Papers section, document discussions and writing on issues considered by the subpanel. The Papers files provide comprehensive presentations of the views of various subpanel experts on selected topics. Meeting files contain summaries and sometimes minute of subpanel discussions of issues. The Reports files, containing several drafts of each report, show the progressive synthesizing of the views of a subpanel's members.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The West Africa Program of the Rockefeller Brothers Fund, launched late in 1957, was designed to provide technical assistance tailored to the economic development needs of Ghana and Nigeria. While the Fund's original resolve to aid Liberia in the same manner proved unfruitful, the Republic of Togo also became a beneficiary of this program in a minor way.

Under the limits established by the Fund, the West Africa Program did not operate as a grant-making agency. At the request of ministries in one of the African governments involved or of a private group of investors and industrialists, the Fund contracted with outside consultants to prepare "feasibility studies." Each of these studies dealt in depth with a specific aspect of the concerned nation's economic potential or needs and was designed to provide a realistic framework for later action. The Fund's responsibility ended with the submission of these studies to the appropriate agencies or private groups.

The Program's main office in Lagos, Nigeria was also a distribution point for these studies. Its director, Robert I. Fleming, acted as a liaison between the governments of Togo, Ghana, and Nigeria and groups of U.S. investors. The Lagos office organized investigative tours for these investors and arranged their contacts with governmental personnel.
The West Africa Program of the Rockefeller Brothers Fund was concluded at the end of 1962.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The records of the West Africa Program include correspondence from the New York and Lagos offices, memoranda, reports, administrative and financial materials, personnel correspondence, and a complete set of feasibility studies contracted by the Rockefeller Brothers Fund. The bulk of this material dates between 1957 and 1963, the period during which the Lagos office was in full operation.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Biography of President Ramon Magsaysay

Ramón del Fierro Magsaysay (b.August 31, 1907 – d.March 17, 1957) served as president of the Republic of the Philippines from December 30, 1953 until his death in a plane crash in 1957. President Magsaysay was best known for successfully defeating the communist-led Hukbalahap (Huk) movement, and for introducing reform to various aspects of Filipino life.(1) He was extremely popular with the Filipino people and was universally respected for his integrity and his dedication to the betterment of all humankind.
Magsaysay Credo

I believe that government starts at the bottom and moves upward, for government exists for the welfare of the masses of the nation. I believe that he who has less in life should have more in law. I believe that the little man is fundamentally entitled to a little bit more food in his stomach, a little more cloth in his back and a little more roof over his head. I believe that this nation is endowed with a vibrant and stout heart, and possesses untapped capabilities and incredible resiliency. I believe that a high and unwavering sense of morality should pervade all spheres of governmental activity. I believe that the pulse of government should be strong and steady, and the men at the helm imbued with missionary zeal. I believe in the majesty of constitutional and legal processes, in the inviolability of human rights. I believe that the free world is collectively strong, and that there is neither need or reason to compromise the dignity of man. I believe that communism is iniquity, as is the violence it does to the principles of Christianity. I believe that the President should set the example of a big heart, an honest mind, sound instincts, the virtue of healthy impatience and an abiding love for the common man.
Organizational History of the Ramon Magsaysay Award Foundation

The Ramon Magsaysay Award Foundation (RMAF) was established in 1957 in memory of the late President Magsaysay who died in a place crash that same year. President Magsaysay was well-known for his good nature and commitment to justice for all people. Consequently, his death devastated not just the people of the Philippines, but the global community which included the Rockefeller brothers. Just six weeks after learning of the death of Ramon Magsaysay, John D. Rockefeller 3rd wrote to President Carlos P. Garcia, who succeeded President Magsaysay, and proposed that an award be given in honor of President Magsaysay. He wrote:

"My brothers and I have followed closely President Magsaysay's life and work. We believe deeply in that for which he stood… The trustees of the Rockefeller Brothers Fund would consider it a privilege to have a part in establishing a living memorial to the late President. They have authorized me to suggest the creation of the Ramon Magsaysay Award to be given annually to one or more persons in Asia whose demonstrated leadership is motive by a concern for the welfare of people comparable to that which characterized the life of Ramon Magsaysay."(2)

President Garcia accepted the Rockefeller Brothers Fund's proposal. As described on the Ramon Magsaysay Award Foundation's website, "[w]ith the concurrence of the Philippine government, the trustees of the Rockefeller Brothers Fund (RBF) established the Award to honor his memory and perpetuate his example of integrity in public service and pragmatic idealism within a democratic society".(3) The RBF supplied the initial endowment and the RMAF was formally organized in May 1957.

The RMAF is a non-profit corporation run by a seven person, all-Filipino, Board of Trustees. The RMAF is based in Manila, Philippines, and has operated out of the Ramon Magsaysay Center since 1968, when the building opened. Income earned from the Ramon Magsaysay Center has helps to support and sustain the RMAF.

The first awards were given in 1958. Since then, each year one award was given in each of the following five categories: Government Service (GS), Public Service (PS), Community Leadership (CL), Journalism and Literature (JL) and International Understanding (IU, later PIU). In 1964, the Journalism and Literature category was amended to include Creative Communication Arts (JLCCA). Then, in 2000, thanks to a grant from the Ford Foundation, a sixth category for Emergent Leadership (EL) was added. After 2008, the awards were no longer given according to category, except for Emergent Leadership. As described on the RMAF website, "[t]he Ramon Magsaysay Award is given to persons – regardless of race, nationality, creed or gender – who address issues of human development in Asia with courage and creativity, and in doing so have made contributions which have transformed their societies".(4) Since, 1958, the award has been given to a diverse group of individuals and organizations.
The award ceremonies are held every year on August 31st, the anniversary of the birth of President Magsaysay. During the days surrounding the award ceremony, awardees and guests attend a series of events given in their honor. These events include the laying of wreaths at the Rizal Monument and in front of Ramon Magsaysay's tomb, luncheons for the awardees, and calls on the current President of the Philippines and on Mrs. Luz Magsaysay, the wife of President Magsaysay. Additionally, the awardees are asked to lead a discussion or give a presentation on a subject related to the work for which they were acknowledged.
(1) Encyclopædia Britannica Online, s. v. "Ramon Magsaysay," accessed January 03, 2012, http://0-www.britannica.com.libcat.lafayette.edu/EBchecked/topic/357732/Ramon-Magsaysay.
(2) The Ramon Magsaysay Awards: 1958 – 1962. 9-10.
(3) Ramon Magsaysay Award Foundation Website. "History". (accessed on June 2, 2011) http://www.rmaf.org.ph/?id=2&page=history
(4) Ibid.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Contains a scrapbook for each year that the Ramon Magsaysay Award was given from 1958-1998, with the exception of 1996 and 1997. In each given year, a scrapbook was completed shortly after the award ceremonies had ended. The scrapbooks were then sent to the Rockefeller Brothers Fund (RBF).

The material within each scrapbook includes media coverage leading up to the award ceremony, documentation of the ceremony itself, and the post-event departures of the awardees. Most scrapbooks feature newspaper clippings, responses given by the awardees at the ceremonies, photographs of the various events related to the awards, and copies of materials handed out during informal group discussions given by the awardees.

There were no awards given in 1970 because the government of the Philippines asked that institutions conserve all foreign currency. No awards given in 1990 out of respect for the people of the Philippines who had just experienced a terrible earthquake on July 16th, 1990.
In this record, categories of awards will be abreviated in the following fashion:

Award Category Abbreviations are as follows: Government Service (GS) Public Service (PS) Community Leadership (CL) Journalism and Literature (JL) International Understanding (IU) Peace & International Understanding (PIU) Journalism, Literature and Creative Communication Arts (JLCCA) Emergent Leadership (EL)

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged chronological by the year the award was given. Original order was maintained within each scrapbook, and pages numbers were assigned, found in the upper right-hand corner of each sleeve.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: All archival material 10 years old or older is open for scholarly research.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: The Rockefeller Brothers Fund retains legal title, copyright and literary property rights in the records. The Rockefeller Archive Center has authority to grant permission to cite and publish material from the records. Requests to publish works in their entirety will be referred to the officers of the Rockefeller Brothers Fund.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Rockefeller Brothers Fund has deposited these records at the Rockefeller Archive Center. The Archive Center received the scrapbooks in multiple accessions beginning in 1979 and continuing periodically through 2006.

phystech.head: Physical Characteristics and Technical Requirements
phystech.p: The scrapbooks were originally housed in maroon covers inscribed with the year. Archival photocopies of each cover can be found in the collection. To enable long-term preservation of the original materials, the support pages of the scrapbooks were removed from their bindings and re-housed in polypropylene sleeves.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Advanced archival processing of the Ramon Magsaysay Scrapbooks was conducted by Julia Welby, Summer Intern, Rockefeller Archive Center, June-August 2011. Processing included arranging and describing the records and preparing them for scholarly access. Advanced work focused on the re-housing and item-level care of each individual scrapbook to facilitate their long-term preservation.
